Is there a strong reason why links to other pages in Confluence needs to be checked?

A link should only be checked for permission when it's clicked by a user.

If there a page contains a lot of links, this will reduce performance due to the permission checking involved.

The autocomplete on QA-EAC is showing things centred due to the CSS rule in fixed-width CSS:
{code}
body {
    background: #d5d5d5 url("gradient-background.gif") 50% 0 repeat-y;
    text-align: center;
}
{code}

The problem with putting text-align on the body tag is that various elements are appended to the body, both from Confluence and plug-ins, and it shouldn't be the element's responsibility to override a non-standard CSS property.

The easy solution is to wrap the full-height-container div in another div and center that div.

